The National Cooperative Bank is a congressionally chartered cooperative bank in the United States created by the National Consumer Cooperative Bank Act of 1978 (Pub.L. 95-351). With $2.2 billion in assets at the end of 2015, the NCB primarily provides commercial banking services to other cooperative enterprises, but also has a small retail branch network in Ohio and several national branches.
Capital Impact Partners was the non-profit community development financial institution subsidiary of the NCB. It became a stand-alone organization in 2014.
